<ENAMEX TYPE="ORG">The United Nations World Food Program</ENAMEX> , <ENAMEX TYPE="ORG">WFP</ENAMEX> , says <ENAMEX TYPE="CARDINAL">up to a million</ENAMEX> people in <ENAMEX TYPE="GPE">Afghanistan</ENAMEX> could die of starvation unless it receives more aid from donors .
The country has been hit by its worst drought in <ENAMEX TYPE="DATE">30 years</ENAMEX> .
This report from <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Katy Clark</ENAMEX> .
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORG">The World Food Program</ENAMEX> says its stocks of food aid are due to run out in <ENAMEX TYPE="DATE">February</ENAMEX> , <ENAMEX TYPE="DATE">months</ENAMEX> before the next harvest in <ENAMEX TYPE="DATE">June</ENAMEX> .
Donations of wheat for <ENAMEX TYPE="GPE">Afghanistan</ENAMEX> have traditionally come from western governments .
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORG">WFP</ENAMEX> blames general donor fatigue for their inadequate response , but is pleading for donors to give more food aid for <ENAMEX TYPE="GPE">Afghanistan</ENAMEX> or face a catastrophe .
Conditions in many parts of the country are at crisis point .
Many families have already sold their livestock and household goods to buy food , and still have only <ENAMEX TYPE="CARDINAL">1</ENAMEX> or <ENAMEX TYPE="DATE">2 months</ENAMEX> of starvation rations left .
<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Katy Clark</ENAMEX> , <ENAMEX TYPE="ORG">BBC News</ENAMEX> , <ENAMEX TYPE="GPE">Islamabad</ENAMEX> .
